Subject: monitor-recovery safety net: never leave the physical monitor disabled

User reported their physical monitor stayed dark after an apollo session
even though the in-process `[VDISPLAY] Restored kscreen primary to: DP-3`
log line ran. They had to SSH in and re-enable the output via CLI.
That is a hard "must never happen again" rule.

The existing flow relies on apollo's `on_evdi_removed()` running before
the process exits. But three classes of failure skip that:

  * SIGSEGV / SIGABRT inside the encoder, capture loop, or kscreen
    JSON parse, before the cleanup branch runs.
  * SIGKILL from the OOM killer (apollo peaked at 9G RSS in the
    journal — the kernel WILL kill it under memory pressure and
    SIGKILL cannot be caught).
  * Hard power-off or kernel panic.

In every case the on-disk kwin state shows the physical primary
disabled and the user has no working desktop.

This patch adds a small, crash-safe state file:

  $XDG_STATE_HOME/apollo/saved-primary  (typically ~/.local/state/apollo/saved-primary)

written atomically the moment apollo disables a physical output, and
deleted on clean restore. Two independent recovery paths consult it:

  1. apollo's openVDisplayDevice() calls a new kscreen::recover_on_startup()
     before doing ANYTHING else. If a previous session left the file
     behind, we run `kscreen-doctor output.<name>.enable
     output.<name>.priority.1` and delete the file. Triggers when the
     user restarts apollo after a crash, OR on the next boot's auto-start.

  2. The systemd user unit now has `ExecStopPost=-/usr/bin/apollo-monitor-recovery`.
     systemd runs ExecStopPost after the main process exits even if it
     was killed by SIGKILL. The script reads the same state file and
     runs the same kscreen-doctor command. Triggers immediately when
     apollo dies for any reason, before the user notices.

The two paths overlap intentionally — belt and suspenders. If one
fails (e.g. kscreen-doctor not yet available in the systemd execution
environment) the other still catches it.

Pure addition: no change to the normal-shutdown code path, no change
to the EVDI capture / encoder / fps behaviour.

--- a/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
+++ b/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
@@ -298,7 +298,89 @@
     static std::mutex state_mutex;
     static int evdi_active_count = 0;
     static std::string saved_primary;
 
+    // Patch 0021: crash-safe monitor recovery.
+    //
+    // The in-memory `saved_primary` is lost if apollo dies between
+    // wait_and_promote_new_to_primary() and on_evdi_removed() — SIGSEGV,
+    // SIGKILL/OOM, hard power-off, etc. That left the user's physical
+    // monitor disabled with no way to recover except SSH-ing in.
+    //
+    // We now also write `saved_primary` to a small state file the moment
+    // we disable a physical output, and delete it on clean restore. On
+    // every apollo startup we look for a stale state file and, if present,
+    // run the same restore command before doing anything else. Combined
+    // with systemd ExecStopPost (which runs even after SIGKILL), this
+    // guarantees the physical monitor comes back.
+    static std::string state_file_path() {
+      // Prefer $XDG_STATE_HOME, then $HOME/.local/state, then $HOME/.cache.
+      const char *xdg_state = std::getenv("XDG_STATE_HOME");
+      const char *home = std::getenv("HOME");
+      std::string base;
+      if (xdg_state && xdg_state[0]) {
+        base = std::string(xdg_state) + "/apollo";
+      } else if (home && home[0]) {
+        base = std::string(home) + "/.local/state/apollo";
+      } else {
+        return "";  // no usable path
+      }
+      // mkdir -p (best-effort)
+      std::error_code ec;
+      fs::create_directories(base, ec);
+      return base + "/saved-primary";
+    }
+
+    // Write `name` atomically: write to .tmp, rename. Safe to call from
+    // any thread. Returns true on success.
+    static bool write_state_file(const std::string &name) {
+      const std::string path = state_file_path();
+      if (path.empty()) {
+        return false;
+      }
+      const std::string tmp = path + ".tmp";
+      {
+        std::ofstream f(tmp, std::ios::binary | std::ios::trunc);
+        if (!f) {
+          return false;
+        }
+        f << name;
+      }
+      std::error_code ec;
+      fs::rename(tmp, path, ec);
+      if (ec) {
+        fs::remove(tmp, ec);
+        return false;
+      }
+      return true;
+    }
+
+    static std::string read_state_file() {
+      const std::string path = state_file_path();
+      if (path.empty()) {
+        return "";
+      }
+      std::ifstream f(path);
+      if (!f) {
+        return "";
+      }
+      std::string out;
+      std::getline(f, out);
+      // strip trailing whitespace / newlines defensively
+      while (!out.empty() && (out.back() == '\n' || out.back() == '\r' || out.back() == ' ')) {
+        out.pop_back();
+      }
+      return out;
+    }
+
+    static void delete_state_file() {
+      const std::string path = state_file_path();
+      if (path.empty()) {
+        return;
+      }
+      std::error_code ec;
+      fs::remove(path, ec);
+    }
+
     static std::string run_capture(const std::string &cmd) {
       std::array<char, 4096> buf {};
       std::string out;
@@ -468,6 +551,19 @@
           saved_primary.clear();
         } else {
           saved_primary = original_primary;
+          // Patch 0021: persist saved_primary to disk BEFORE we disable the
+          // physical output. If apollo dies before on_evdi_removed runs
+          // (SIGSEGV, SIGKILL/OOM, hard reset, etc.), the next apollo
+          // startup or the systemd ExecStopPost script will read this file
+          // and re-enable the physical monitor. Failure is non-fatal — we
+          // just lose the safety net for this session.
+          if (!write_state_file(saved_primary)) {
+            BOOST_LOG(warning) << "[VDISPLAY/kscreen] could not write recovery state file at "
+                               << state_file_path() << " — physical monitor will NOT auto-recover if apollo crashes";
+          } else {
+            BOOST_LOG(info) << "[VDISPLAY/kscreen] wrote recovery state file: "
+                            << state_file_path() << " (saved_primary=" << saved_primary << ")";
+          }
         }
       }
       ++evdi_active_count;
@@ -511,9 +606,36 @@
           BOOST_LOG(info) << "[VDISPLAY] Restored kscreen primary to: " << saved_primary << " (re-enabled and promoted)";
         }
         saved_primary.clear();
+        // Patch 0021: clean restore done — remove the recovery state file
+        // so the next apollo startup doesn't try to "recover" something
+        // that's already in the user's desired state.
+        delete_state_file();
       }
     }
 
+    // Patch 0021: called from openVDisplayDevice() on apollo startup. If a
+    // previous apollo session crashed (SIGSEGV, SIGKILL/OOM, power loss)
+    // between disabling the physical primary and restoring it, the state
+    // file persists. Read it, re-enable + promote, and clear the file.
+    // No-op when there's no stale state.
+    void recover_on_startup() {
+      const std::string prev = read_state_file();
+      if (prev.empty()) {
+        return;
+      }
+      if (!is_safe_name(prev)) {
+        BOOST_LOG(warning) << "[VDISPLAY/kscreen] state file contained unsafe name; refusing to use: "
+                           << prev;
+        delete_state_file();
+        return;
+      }
+      BOOST_LOG(info) << "[VDISPLAY/kscreen] previous apollo session did not clean up "
+                      << "(state file present); restoring " << prev << " as primary";
+      const std::string cmd = "kscreen-doctor output." + prev + ".enable output." + prev + ".priority.1";
+      run_status(cmd);
+      delete_state_file();
+    }
+
   }  // namespace kscreen
 
   // ============================================================================
@@ -1060,6 +1141,14 @@
 
     BOOST_LOG(info) << "[VDISPLAY] Initializing Linux virtual display driver...";
 
+    // Patch 0021: monitor-recovery safety net. If the previous apollo
+    // session was killed (SIGSEGV, SIGKILL/OOM, hard power-off) between
+    // disabling the physical primary and restoring it, the user is left
+    // staring at a dark physical monitor with no easy fix. recover_on_startup
+    // reads the persisted "saved_primary" state file and runs kscreen-doctor
+    // to re-enable it. No-op when the previous session shut down cleanly.
+    kscreen::recover_on_startup();
+
     // Wipe stale EVDI cards from any prior crashed run BEFORE Apollo's
     // encoder probe scans /dev/dri/* — otherwise mesa gbm_create_device
     // SIGSEGVs on the orphaned card.
--- a/packaging/linux/sunshine.service.in
+++ b/packaging/linux/sunshine.service.in
@@ -8,6 +8,11 @@
 ExecStartPre=/bin/sleep 5
 @SUNSHINE_SERVICE_START_COMMAND@
 @SUNSHINE_SERVICE_STOP_COMMAND@
+# Patch 0021: ALWAYS run the monitor-recovery script after apollo exits,
+# even after SIGKILL/OOM. The "-" prefix tells systemd to ignore the exit
+# code so a clean shutdown (where there's nothing to restore) doesn't
+# leave the unit in a "failed" state.
+ExecStopPost=-/usr/bin/apollo-monitor-recovery
 Restart=on-failure
 RestartSec=5s
 
